The [[2014–15 Premier League|2014–15 season]] is [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]]'s seventh season in the [[Premier League]] and the 59th in the [[English football league system|top tier of English football]].

In preparation for the 2014–15 season [[Mark Hughes]] signed [[Phil Bardsley]], [[Mame Biram Diouf]], [[Bojan Krkić]], [[Steve Sidwell]], [[Dionatan Teixeira]] whilst [[Victor Moses]] and [[Oussama Assaidi]] joined on season-long loans. Departing the [[Britannia Stadium]] were [[Matthew Etherington]], [[Cameron Jerome]], [[Michael Kightly]] and [[Ryan Shotton]]. Stoke had a mixed start to the season as they lost 1–0 at home to [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]], drew 1–1 with [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] and then beat the reigning league champions [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] 1–0. This set the tone for an inconsistent Autumn as Stoke managed just three wins in September, October and November and lost at home to newly promoted sides [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] and [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]].

Results improved in December as the Potters beat [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] 3–2, [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] and [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] both 1–0. Stoke suffered a number of injuries in January most notably to Bojan but the side were still able to secure victories against Leicester City and Queens Park Rangers. Stoke's only arrival in the January transfer window was German centre-back [[Philipp Wollscheid]] on loan from [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]]. After drawing 1–1 at Newcastle United, Stoke suffered back-to-back 4–1 defeats to Manchester City and then in the [[FA Cup]] to [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]]. Stoke recovered well from this set-back winning their next three matches against Aston Villa, Hull City and Everton. This was the followed by three defeats against West Brom, Crystal Palace and Chelsea. Stoke ended the season strongly with victories over Southampton (2–1), Tottenham Hotspur (3–0) and Liverpool (6–1) ensuring a second consecutive 9th-place finish.

==Pre-season==
In March 2014 Stoke announced that from the 2014–15 season their kit will be supplied by American sportswear manufacturer [[Warrior Sports]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Stoke City announce kit deal with Warrior|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Stoke-announce-kit-deal-Warrior/story-20828273-detail/story.html|work=Stoke Sentinel|accessdate=26 April 2014}}</ref> In May 2014 long serving winger [[Matthew Etherington]] was released from the club following the end of his contract as well as under-21 players, [[Lucas Dawson]], [[Kevin Gomez-Nieto]], Ben Heneghan, Jordan Keane, Jordan Richardson and [[Karim Rossi]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Stoke release Matthew Etherington but agree Thomas Sorensen deal|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27554089|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=31 May 2014}}</ref> On 22 May 2014 [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] full-back [[Phil Bardsley]] agreed to join Stoke on a three-year contract.<ref name=Bardsley/> [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] midfielder [[Steve Sidwell]] joined Stoke on a free transfer on 9 June 2014 on a two-year deal having previously worked under [[Mark Hughes]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Steve Sidwell: Stoke City sign former Fulham midfielder|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27769534|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=9 June 2014}}</ref> On 11 June 2014 Stoke made two signings, Senegalese striker [[Mame Biram Diouf]] arrived on a free transfer from [[Hannover 96]] whilst 21-year-old Slovakian defender [[Dionatan Teixeira]] joined from [[FK Dukla Banská Bystrica|Dukla Banská Bystrica]] for an undisclosed fee.<ref name="Diouf and Dion"/> Stoke returned to training on 9 July where they went to nearby [[St George's Park National Football Centre|St George's Park]] for fitness tests.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mame Diouf joins Stoke City squad for first day of pre-season training at St George’s Park|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Pictures-Mame-Diouf-joins-Stoke-City-squad-day/story-21348616-detail/story.html|website=Stoke Sentinel|accessdate=9 July 2014}}</ref> On 18 July 2014 the squad flew out to Germany for a pre-season training camp and friendlies against [[Borussia Mönchengladbach]], [[TSV 1860 München]] and [[FC Schalke 04|Schalke 04]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Stoke City on tour: The Potters in their own pictures|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Stoke-City-tour-pictures/story-21657579-detail/story.html|website=Stoke Sentinel|accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref>

Stoke's first match of pre-season was against [[Borussia Mönchengladbach]] in [[Rottach-Egern]].<ref name="BMG V SCFC">{{cite web|title=Match report: Borussia Monchengladbach 1, Stoke City 1|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Match-report-Borussia-Monchengladbach-1-Stoke/story-21663974-detail/story.html?|website=Stoke Sentinel|accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> Heavy rain delayed kick-off by 20 minutes as manager Mark Hughes decided to give all of his players 45 minutes.<ref name="BMG V SCFC"/> In an eventful first half new signing [[Mame Biram Diouf]] almost saw his early shot parried by [[Christofer Heimeroth]] into the path of [[Andy Wilkinson]] but Heimeroth denied Wilkinson what would have been a rare goal with a fine save.<ref name="BMG V SCFC"/> Just after half time a loose pass by [[Charlie Adam]] was picked up by [[Thorgan Hazard]] who slid the ball past [[Thomas Sørensen]]. Stoke earned a 1–1 draw after [[Jonathan Walters]] battled his way through the Borussia defence and set-up [[Peter Crouch]] for a simple tap-in.<ref name="BMG V SCFC"/> On 22 July 2014 Stoke completed the signing of [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] forward [[Bojan Krkić]] for an undisclosed fee.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bojan Krkic: Stoke sign Barcelona forward on four-year deal|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28430289|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=23 July 2014}}</ref> Stoke's second pre-season encounter was a 2–0 defeat against [[TSV 1860 München]] with goals from [[Daniel Adlung]] and  [[Bobby Wood (soccer)|Bobby Wood]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Match report: Stoke City 0, 1860 TSV Munich 2|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Match-report-Stoke-City-0-1860-TSV-Munich-2/story-21944898-detail/story.html|website=Stoke Sentinel|accessdate=28 July 2014}}</ref> Stoke's final game of their training camp was against [[FC Schalke 04|Schalke 04]] in [[Kufstein]] just over the border in Austria. In an even first half [[Marko Arnautović]] had a penalty well saved by [[Ralf Fährmann]]. Bojan scored his first Stoke goal just after half time after being put through one on one by [[Stephen Ireland]]. However Schalke responded quickly with a header from [[Joël Matip]]. [[Dionatan Teixeira]] then had a goal disallowed for offside before a late strike from [[Tranquillo Barnetta]] earned Schalke the win.<ref>{{cite web|title=Match report: Schalke 2, Stoke City 1|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Match-report-Schalke-2-Stoke-City-1/story-22013429-detail/story.html|website=Stoke Sentinel|accessdate=31 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140814160306/http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Match-report-Schalke-2-Stoke-City-1/story-22013429-detail/story.html|archive-date=14 August 2014|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

Upon their return to England Hughes split his squad for games against [[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion]] and [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]]. Both matches were drawn firstly 0–0 with Burton and 1–1 with Blackburn with Bojan scoring his second pre-season goal.<ref>{{cite web|title=Full-time report: Burton 0, Stoke City 0|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/time-report-Burton-0-Stoke-City-0/story-22055999-detail/story.html|website=Stoke Sentinel|accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Match Report: Blackburn Rovers 1 Stoke City 1: Bojan the little matador|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Match-Report-Blackburn-Rovers-1-Stoke-City-1/story-22061282-detail/story.html|website=Stoke Sentinel|accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref> On 6 August 2014 Stoke played their only home friendly of pre-season against Spanish outfit [[Real Betis]]. A period of good one-touch build up play led to [[Phil Bardsley]] crossing across the face of goal for [[Erik Pieters]] to tap in. Stoke made it 2–0 after Bojan won the ball on the half way line and ran through and fired past [[Antonio Adán]] for his third pre-season goal and earned Stoke their first win.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Bojan legend grows... and it's still only pre-season|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Stoke-City/story-22123958-detail/story.html|website=Stoke Sentinel|accessdate=7 August 2014}}</ref> Stoke's final match of pre-season was back in Germany where they played out a 1–1 draw with [[SC Freiburg]] at the [[Dreisamstadion]]. [[Mame Biram Diouf]] scored his first goal for Stoke cancelling out an early goal from [[Pavel Krmaš]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Match report: Freiburg 1, Stoke City 1|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Match-report-Freiburg-1-Stoke-City-1/story-22284808-detail/story.html|website=Stoke Sentinel|accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref>

